%N A329278 Irregular table read by rows. The n-th row is the permutation of {0, 1, 2, ..., 2^n-1} given by T(n,k) = k(k+1)/2 (mod 2^n).
%C A329278 Conjecture: for n > 0, the n-th row has 2^(n-1)-1 descents.
%C A329278 T(n,k) = A000217(k) for 0 <= k <= A017911(n+1), and T(n,2^n-1) = 2^(n-1).
%C A329278 Using T(n,k) we always can construct semimagic square of size 2^n X 2^n for n >= 0 (with a single exception at n = 1). To do this, take a square matrix M of size 2^n X 2^n and apply M(i,j) = 1 + ((j-i) mod 2^n)*2^n + [(j-i) even]*s(n,i) + [(j-i) odd]*(2^n - s(n,i) - 1) for 0 <= i,j < 2^n where T(n,s(n,k)) = k (see Jack Edward Tisdell link). - _Mikhail Kurkov_, Feb 06 2026
